Several recent papers have explored the application of deep learning techniques for defect detection in semiconductor manufacturing. Here are some key developments in this area:

## Wafer Defect Map Classification

Researchers have applied deep learning models to classify defect patterns on wafer maps:

- A 2022 study introduced a hybrid classical-quantum deep learning approach for wafer defect map classification[4]. The authors proposed using quantum circuits to enhance the learning capabilities of classical deep neural networks for this task.

- Another paper from 2019 employed convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and extreme gradient boosting (XGBoost) for wafer map defect pattern classification and retrieval[6]. 

## Defect Detection in Wafer Buffer Zones

A 2024 paper presented a deep learning method specifically for detecting defects in wafer buffer zones[1]:

- The authors modified the Xception CNN architecture to fit wafer data characteristics.
- They achieved 96.9% accuracy on a real wafer dataset.
- Class activation mapping was used to estimate defect sizes.

## General Semiconductor Defect Detection

Other papers have explored broader applications of deep learning for semiconductor defect detection:

- A 2023 study proposed a two-step approach combining traditional computer vision with a lightweight SqueezeNet CNN for defect detection and classification on semiconductor wafers[2].

- Researchers in 2021 developed an adversarial network architecture based on conditional GANs for defect detection in semiconductor manufacturing processes[7].

## Quantum-Enhanced Approaches

Some recent work has investigated integrating quantum computing concepts:

- A 2022 paper presented quantum computing-based deep learning methods for semiconductor defect detection, including wafer defect map classification, defect pattern classification, and hotspot detection[3][8].

The researchers explored parametrized quantum circuits with different expressibility to enhance classical deep learning models.

In summary, deep learning approaches like CNNs are being widely applied and customized for various semiconductor defect detection tasks. There is also emerging interest in quantum-enhanced machine learning techniques for potentially improved performance. The field continues to evolve rapidly as researchers develop more sophisticated and targeted deep learning models for this critical manufacturing application.

